  <div class="container">
 
    <div class="row align-items-center g-5">
 
      <!-- left -->
      <div class="col-lg-4">
        <div class="waste-image">
          <img
            src="pbl_image/learn_hand_with_plastic.png"
            alt="Waste Image"
          />
        </div>
      </div>
 
      <!-- right -->
      <div class="col-lg-8">
 
        <h1 class="section-title2">Types of Waste</h1>
 
        <p class="section-text">
          Waste is piling up around us every day—from our homes, schools,
          and cities—and it continues to grow as populations and consumption
          increase. This rising volume of waste puts pressure on the environment
          and makes proper management more important than ever.
        </p>
 
        <p class="section-text">
          However, not all waste is the same. Different types of waste behave
          differently and require specific methods of handling and disposal.
          In general, waste can be divided into four main categories:
          biodegradable, non-biodegradable, recyclable, and hazardous.
        </p>
 
        <!-- Waste Types -->
        <div class="row mt-5">
 
          <div class="col-md-6">
            <div class="waste-card">
 
              <div class="icon-box">
                <i class="bi bi-tree-fill"></i>
              </div>
 
              <div>
                <h5>Biodegradable Waste</h5>
                <p>
                  Organic materials such as food scraps and leaves that
                  decompose naturally and can be composted.
                </p>
              </div>
 
            </div>
          </div>
 
          <div class="col-md-6">
            <div class="waste-card">
 
              <div class="icon-box">
                <i class="bi bi-cup-straw"></i>
              </div>
 
              <div>
                <h5>Non-biodegradable Waste</h5>
                <p>
                  Materials like plastics and metals that do not break down
                  easily and can remain in the environment for a long time.
                </p>
              </div>
 
            </div>
          </div>
 
          <div class="col-md-6">
            <div class="waste-card">
 
              <div class="icon-box">
                 <i class="bi bi-recycle"></i>
              </div>
 
              <div>
                <h5>Recyclable Waste</h5>
                <p>
                  Items such as paper, glass, and plastic that can be
                  processed and turned into new products.
                </p>
              </div>
 
            </div>
          </div>
 
          <div class="col-md-6">
            <div class="waste-card">
 
              <div class="icon-box">
                <i class="bi bi-battery-charging"></i>
              </div>
 
              <div>
                <h5>Hazardous Waste</h5>
                <p>
                  Dangerous materials like batteries and chemicals that
                  require special handling to prevent harm.
                </p>
              </div>
 
            </div>
          </div>
 
        </div>
 
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
    
